06493nam a22007215i 9789633861974DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023hu     fo  d z      eng d  a97896338619747 a10.1515/97896338619742doi  a(DE-B1597)633433  a(OCoLC)1398466461  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 7aPOL0420202bisacsh00aUnderground Streams :bNational-Conservatives after World War II in Communist Hungary and Eastern Europe /ced. by János M. Rainer. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Acronyms and Abbreviations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Underground Streams: National-Conservatives after World War II in Communist Hungary and Eastern Europe -- tPart One: The Right-Wing Tradition in Eastern Europe after 1945 -- t1. The Romanian Ideology: Merging Political Extremes in a National Stalinist Discourse -- t2. Absent Traditions: Right-Wing Strands in Slovakian Politics -- t3. A Round-Trip through the Czech Lands: The Origins of a Liberal Right Revolution -- t4. Conservative Right-Wing Political Thinking in Hungary after 1945 -- tPart Two: Right-Wing Enemies through the Lens of State Security -- t5. Social Resistance under the Kádár Regime and the “Right-Wing” Enemies of State Security -- t6. Christian Democrats under Fire from the Political Police, 1945–1989 -- t7. “Petty” Arrow Cross Supporters in the Interior Ministry Files -- tPart Three: Personal Life Paths and Strategies -- t8. “I Was Brought up the Old Way, I’m a Conservative”: A Middle-Class Christian Looks Back on His Life -- t9. A Nationalist of Successive Periods: Miklós Mester (1906–1989) -- t10. From Right to Left – or Not? Béla Csikós – Nagy, a Paradigmatical Opportunist of Transition -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors of this edited volume address the hidden attraction that existed between the extremes of left and right, and of internationalism and nationalism under the decades of communist dictatorship in Eastern Europe. One might suppose that under the suppressive regimes based on leftist ideology and internationalism their right-wing opponents would have been defeated and ultimately removed. These essays, on the other hand, recount the itinerary of survival and revival of "right-wing" thought and activities under communist dictatorship. Resistance and accommodation are explored in the various phases from the Stalinist era to the demise of the Soviet Bloc, with the continuity provided by tacit or concealed right-wing discourses receiving particular consideration. The Eastern European right, both in its conservative and fascist version, centered on nationalism, a legitimizing factor that increased with the downfall of the regimes, and the authors thus accord nationalism special attention. Two documentary sources for these essays that stand out are files of the security services and the exceptionally rich Oral History Archive compiled by the 1956 Institute in Budapest, Hungary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Conservatism & Liberalism.2bisacsh  aNationalism, Accommodation, Central Europe, Regime change, Oral history, Political right.1 aIacob, Bogdan C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKőrösi, Zsuzsanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLénárt, András, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaksa, Rudolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRainer, János M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l